These environment variables are now defined with empty values, which means they will always be set (to empty strings) if not provided by the host environment. This differs from the previous behavior where they defaulted to empty with `${VAR:-}` syntax. Empty string values may cause boto3 to fail differently than undefined variables. Consider using the `${AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID}` syntax without the colon to only pass through if defined in the host environment, or document that users must have these variables set before running docker compose.
```suggestion
      AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID: ${AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID}
      AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY: ${AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY}
      AWS_SESSION_TOKEN: ${AWS_SESSION_TOKEN}
```

The workflow lacks error handling. If the Docker build or push fails, there's no cleanup or notification. Consider adding error handling or at minimum ensuring the workflow fails fast. Additionally, consider adding a step to verify the image was successfully pushed to ECR.
```suggestion
        run: |
          set -euo pipefail
          IMAGE_TAG=${GITHUB_SHA::7}
          ECR_URI=${AWS_ACCOUNT_ID}.dkr.ecr.${AWS_REGION}.amazonaws.com/${AWS_ECR_REPOSITORY}
          docker build -t ${ECR_URI}:${IMAGE_TAG} .
          docker push ${ECR_URI}:${IMAGE_TAG}
          # Verify image was pushed to ECR
          aws ecr describe-images --repository-name ${AWS_ECR_REPOSITORY} --image-ids imageTag=${IMAGE_TAG}
```

AWS account ID and IAM role ARN are hardcoded in the workflow. These sensitive values should be stored as GitHub secrets or repository/organization variables for better security and flexibility across environments. Consider using:
```yaml
AWS_IAM_ROLE: ${{ secrets.AWS_IAM_ROLE }}
AWS_ACCOUNT_ID: ${{ secrets.AWS_ACCOUNT_ID }}
```
```suggestion
  AWS_IAM_ROLE: ${{ secrets.AWS_IAM_ROLE }}
  AWS_ECR_REPOSITORY: aot/aot-user-ui
  AWS_ACCOUNT_ID: ${{ secrets.AWS_ACCOUNT_ID }}
```
